Joseph Shabalala had reason to be arrogant: the musical group he formed, Ladysmith Black Mambazo, won five American Grammy music awards â€“ more than any other African group. And superstar Paul Simon turned to the group when he wanted to explore new areas with his album Graceland in 1986. Though his music and rhythms may have been complex, Shabalala remained, at heart, a simple man, deeply committed both to Christianity and his Zulu culture. In the latter he proved that, even in a time of huge technology change globally, cultures can not only survive, but thrive. When he died yesterday,...